'''Inger Zachrisson''' (born 1936) is a Swedish archaeologist specializing in the history of the [[Sami people]]. As Associate Professor of Archaeology at [[Uppsala University]] and former curator of Stockholm's [[Swedish History Museum|History Museum]], she has researched Sami archaeology and history since the [[Iron Age]].<ref name=littvet>{{cite web|url=http://www.littvet.uu.se/digitalAssets/554/554850_3vvpp-19-oktober-inger-zachrisson.pdf|title=South Saami prehistory in Mid-Scandinavia|publisher=Uppsala University|accessdate=19 October 2016 |language=}}</ref><ref name="Roslund2007">{{cite book|last=Roslund|first=Mats|title=Guests in the House: Cultural Transmission between Slavs and Scandinavians 900 to 1300 AD|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1POvCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA113|year=2007|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-474-2185-6|pages=113–}}</ref>
Zachrisson ran the South Sami project from 1984 to 1998, leading to her ''Möten i gränsland. Samer och germaner i Mellanskandinavien'' (Encounters in Border Country: Saami and Germanic peoples in central Scandinavia), published in 1997. She has revealed that from the Late Stone Age in [[Scandinavia]], there were two cultural traditions, the Sami in the north-east and the Scandinavians in the south-west. Her archaeological finds and linguistic analyses show that from the year dot until 1300 AD, there were increasing contacts between the two groups.<ref name=littvet/> Her work on the 11th and 12th-century burial site [[Vivallen]] in [[Härjedalen]] on the Swedish-Norwegian border showed that what had been considered to be Viking graves were in fact Viking merchants buried in the Sami tradition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=4416&artikel=6372241|title=Historiska museet lyfter fram samernas roll under vikingatiden|publisher=Sveriges Radio|accessdate=19 October 2016 |language=Swedish}}</ref> Findings of wool and linen clothing, brooches and rings at the site also demonstrated the level of contact between the Scandinavians and the Sami who maintained their non-Christian traditions.<ref name="DuBois1999">{{cite book|last=DuBois|first=Thomas|title=Nordic Religions in the Viking Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g2-Lga0r62MC&pg=PA23|year=1999|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=0-8122-1714-4|pages=23–}}</ref>
==Publications in English== *{{cite book|last1=Odelberg|first1=Maj|last2=Thålin-Bergman|first2=Lena|last3=Zachrisson|first3=Inger|title=Viking ways: on the Viking age in Sweden|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rCjGAAAAIAAJ|year=1980|publisher=The Swedish Institute}} *{{cite book|last=Zachrisson|first=Inger|title=Lapps and Scandinavians: archaeological finds from northern Sweden|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7yenjgEACAAJ|year=1976|publisher=Kungl. Vitterhets- historie- o. antikvitetsakad. : Almqvist & Wiksell international, distr.|isbn=978-91-7402-005-2}} *{{cite book|last=Zachrisson|first=Inger|title=Saami Or Nordic?: A Model For Ethnic Determination of the Northern Swedish Archaeological Material from the Viking Period and the Early Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RbHHjwEACAAJ|year=1985}}
