{{Infobox NRHP | name =Kijik Archeological District | nrhp_type = nhld | nocat = yes | image = Kijik Archaeological District (20357937598).jpg | caption = Scenery in the district | location = {{Address Restricted}}, [[Lake Clark National Park and Preserve]] | nearest_city= [[Port Alsworth, Alaska]] | locmapin = Alaska | coordinates = <!-- address restricted --> | area = {{convert|1920|acre}} | architect= | architecture= | governing_body = [[National Park Service]] | refnum=94001644 | added = October 12, 1994<ref name=nris/> | designated_nrhp_type= October 12, 1994<ref name=nhlsum>{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1805&ResourceType=District|title=Kijik Archeological District|accessdate=2008-01-04|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606085608/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1805&ResourceType=District|archivedate=2011-06-06|df=}}</ref> {{Infobox NRHP |embed=yes | name = Kijik Historic District | nrhp_type = hd | nocat = yes | image = | caption = | location = {{Address Restricted}}, [[Lake Clark National Park and Preserve]] | nearest_city= [[Port Alsworth, Alaska]] | architect = | architecture = | added = January 29, 1979 | area = {{convert|12|acre}} | governing_body = National Park Service | refnum = 79000410<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> }} }}
'''Kijik''' is a [[ghost town]] in [[Lake and Peninsula Borough, Alaska|Lake and Peninsula Borough]], [[Alaska]], United States. An [[Alaskan Athabaskans|Athabascan]] village that was established on the shores of [[Lake Clark (Alaska)|Lake Clark]] in the [[Alaska Range]], its population was recorded at 91 in the [[1880 United States Census]] and declined thereafter, falling to approximately 25 individuals by 1904. Today, the village has been abandoned. The ghost town is located within the bounds of [[Lake Clark National Park and Preserve]].
The historic portion of the village was the subject of archaeological and ethnological research in the 1960s. Interviews with [[Dena'ina]] elders in [[Nondalton, Alaska|Nondalton]] established that the people of Kijik relocated to Old Nondalton (not far from present-day Nondalton) in the early 19th century, probably to be closer to trading posts and the canneries of [[Bristol Bay]]. A survey expedition that visited the site in 1909 reported it to be abandoned. A major archaeological excavation of the historic village took place in 1966, exposing twelve foundational remnants of log houses (many of the houses having apparently been moved to Old Nondalton at the time of the relocation), and two of what appeared to be larger communal structures.<ref name=fieldiana>{{cite journal|title=Kijik: An Historic Tanaina Settlement|journal=Fieldiana. Anthropology|issue=Volume 15|date=January 16, 1970|last1=Vanstone|first1=James|last2=Townsend|first2=Joan|pages=1–202|jstor=29782443}}</ref>
In 1979, twelve acres of the village site were added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] as a [[historic district (United States)|historic district]].<ref name=nris /> A much larger area, encompassing a significant number of archaeological sites related to the habitation and use of the area from at least the 12th century forward, was designated a [[National Historic Landmark District]] in 1994, for the unique concentration of sites related to the inland [[Dena'ina]] people.<ref name="nhlsum"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/oclp/CLI%20PPG_January2009_small.pdf|title=National Park Service Cultural Landscapes Inventory Professional Procedures Guide|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2014-12-05}}</ref>
The community was known by many other names than "Kijik" during its history, including "Lake Clark Village", "Nijik", "Nikhkak", "Nikhak", and "Old Keegik". Its current name has been spelled in a wide variety of ways, including "Keechik", "Keeghik", "Keejik", "Keggik", "Keygik", "Kichak", "Kichik", "Kilchik", and "Kilchikh".
==Demographics== {{US Census population |1880= 91 |1890= 42 |align-fn=center |footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013}}</ref> }}
Kijik first appeared on the 1880 U.S. Census as the unincorporated [[Tinneh]] village of "Kichik."<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=Rr9RAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=%22Agaligamute%22&source=bl&ots=Tzy-F6Dup7&sig=B81GmrTlcKv3jtL_iWMYTwV3FSo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj69sDB-MLUAhXD2T4KHTt1Dc0Q6AEILjAD#v=snippet&q=kijik&f=false</ref> It appeared again on the 1890 U.S. Census as "Nikhkak." It has not reported since and was abandoned after 1900.
