| coordinates       = {{coord|22.996521|S|43.281927|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}
| coordinates_ref =<ref>{{cite web|title=Padre de Gavea – São Conrado, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?safe=off&client=safari&q=pedra+da+gavea+google+maps&ie=UTF8&hq=&hnear=Pedra+da+Gávea&gl=us&t=m&z=15&vpsrc=0&iwloc=A|publisher=[[Google Maps]]|accessdate=September 10, 2013}}</ref>
| type              = }}
'''Pedra da Gávea''' is a [[monolith]]ic [[mountain]] in [[Tijuca Forest]], [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]. Composed of [[granite]] and [[gneiss]], its elevation is {{convert|844|m}}, making it one of the highest mountains in the world that ends directly in the ocean.<ref name="CPRM">{{cite web|url=http://www.cprm.gov.br/geoecoturismo/pedra_gavea/excursaovirtual.html|title=Pedra da Gávea|first1=Antonio Ivo|last1=de Menezes Medina|first2=Edgar|last2=Shinzato|publisher=Geological Survey of Brazil (Companhia de Pesquisa de Recursos Minerais)|language=Portuguese|accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref>  Trails on the mountain were opened up by the local farming population in the early 1800s; today, the site is under the administration of the [[Tijuca National Park]].<ref name=sumorg>{{cite web|title=Pedra da Gávea|url=http://www.summitpost.org/pedra-da-g-vea/150534#_/term_|publisher=SummitPost.org|accessdate=September 10, 2013}}</ref>

The mountain's name translates as ''Rock of the Topsail'', and was given to it during the expedition of Captain [[Gaspar de Lemos]], begun in 1501, and in which the Rio de Janeiro bay (today [[Guanabara Bay]], but after which the city was named) also received its name. The mountain, one of the first in Brazil to be named in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], was named by the expedition's sailors, who compared its silhouette to that of the shape of a [[topsail]] of a [[carrack]] upon sighting it on January 1, 1502. That name in turn came to be given to the [[Gávea]] area of the city of Rio de Janeiro.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.montanhasdorio.com.br/principal_destaque.cfm?contador=11|title=Pedra da Gávea e a mística Cabeça do Imperador|language=Portuguese|year=2004|publisher=montanhasdorio.com.br|work=Montanhas do Rio|accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref>

Differential weathering on one side of the rock has created what is described as a stylized human face. Markings on another face of the rock have been [[Archaeological interest of Pedra da Gávea|described as an inscription]]. Geologists and scientists are nearly in agreement that the "inscription" is the result of erosion and that the "face" is a product of [[pareidolia]]. Furthermore, the consensus of archaeologists and scholars in Brazil is that the mountain should not be viewed as an archaeological site.

== Geology and ecology ==
[[File:Alvorada na Pedra da Gávea.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Stone of Gávea at dawn]]
Located in the Tijuca Range,<ref name=geosurvey>{{cite journal|last=Jones|first=Fred|title=Landslides of Rio de Janeiro and the Serra das Araras Escarpment, Brazil|journal=Geological Survey Professional Paper|publisher=[[University of California]]|year=1973|volume=697–699|page=11|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-CwlAQAAIAAJ&pg=PP25&dq=%22Gavea+Rock%22#v=onepage&q=%22Gavea%20Rock%22&f=false|accessdate=September 10, 2013}}</ref> Pedra da Gávea is 842&nbsp;m (2,762&nbsp;ft) tall, and is a [[granite dome]].<ref name=sumorg /> The flat top of the mountain is capped with a 150&nbsp;m tall layer of granite, whereas underneath, the mound is made up of [[gneiss]].<ref>[[#Migoń|Migoń (2010)]], p. 93.</ref><ref>[[#Twidale|Twidale (1982)]], p. 74.</ref> The former dates to around 450 million years ago, whereas the latter dates to 600 million years.<ref name=geosurvey /> The mountain, much like other stone outcroppings in and around the area, is the result of younger [[Neoproterozoic]] granitoid rocks and thin Cretaceous diabase dikes intruding the older Meso-Neoproterozoic high-grade metasedimentary rocks.<ref>[[#Migoń|Migoń (2010)]], p. 92.</ref>

The contact zone between the upper granite and the lower gneiss is both sub-horizontal and semi-gradual, and the gneissic [[xenolith]]s have a tabular form, which heavily suggests that they were captured from a [[magma chamber]]’s floor by thermal detachment. It has been suggested that Pedra da Gávea "correspond[s] to the bottom of a granitic magma chamber and the original thickness of the granitic body was much larger than the present exposure."<ref name=motoki/> The granitic body of the Pedra da Gávea could also correspond to the eastern extension of the nearby Pedra Branca Granite Massif, according to Akihisa Motoki et al.<ref name=motoki>{{cite journal|last1=Motoki|first1=Akihisa|title=Contato Intrusivo na Base do Corpo Granítico da Pedra da Gávea, Parque Nacional da Tijuca, Rio de Janeiro|date=2005|page=1|url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/motoki5.tripod.com/Ign/19_Unesp_Gavea_12.doc|accessdate=July 31, 2014|publisher=[[Sociedade Brasileira de Geologia]]|display-authors=etal}}</ref>

Differential weathering incised the northern side of the mountain, producing cavities underneath the granite dome.<ref name="CPRM"/><ref name=weathering>[[#Migoń|Migoń (2010)]], p. 94.</ref> The abrupt dome itself is the result of the more durable granite having resisted the aforementioned weathering more so than the softer gneiss.<ref name="CPRM"/> Furthermore, erosion has worn etches into the mountain's sides.<ref name=thejournal>{{cite journal|author=Barbosa, Januário da Cunha|author2=Porto Alegre, Manuel de Araújo|journal=RIHGB|title=Relatório Sobre a Inscrição da Gávea|publisher=[[Brazilian Historic and Geographic Institute]]|year=1839|pages=86–91|url=http://www.ihgb.org.br/pesquisa.php|accessdate=September 9, 2013}} Note: To find the article, one must search for the term "Gávea".</ref><ref name=portugesebook>[[#Turin|Turin (2005)]], p. 103.</ref><ref name=cooper>{{cite journal|last=Clark|first=T. Cooper|title=The XXth International Congress of Americanists|journal=The Pan-American Magazine and New World Review|publisher=[[Indiana University]]|year=1922|volume=36|pages=286–287|url=https://books.google.com/?id=F7sWAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA286&dq=Gavea+Rock+inscription#v=onepage&q=Gavea%20Rock%20inscription&f=false|accessdate=September 9, 2013}}</ref>

The mountain is covered in [[lemon]], [[Orange (fruit)|orange]], [[breadfruit]], [[banana]], and [[papaya]] trees, as well as [[cannas]] and [[rose]]s.<ref name=cooper />

== Archaeological interest ==
{{main|Archaeological interest of Pedra da Gávea}}
There is a purported inscription carved into the rockface, which some claim is in [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]], a [[Semitic language]] known to modern scholars only from inscriptions. According to Paul Herrmann in his book ''Conquests by Man'', the inscription on the mountain had been known for quite some time, but had merely been attributed to "some unknown prehistoric American people".<ref name=her212 /> Closer examination, however, led some researchers to believe it was of Phoenician origin.<ref name=her212>[[#Herrmann|Herrmann (1954)]], p. 212.</ref>  Today, however, most researchers suggest that the inscription and "face" are merely the results of erosion.<ref name=thejournal /><ref name="portugesebook"/><ref name=travelguide>[[#Waggoner|Waggoner (2008)]], pp. 1–650.</ref> In the mid-1950s, the Brazilian Ministry of Education and Health denied that the site featured any writing, declaring "that examination by geologists had proved it to be nothing more than the effect of weather erosion which happened to look like an inscription."<ref name=her214>[[#Herrmann|Herrmann (1954)]], p. 214.</ref> Brazilian archaeologists and scholars have adopted a negative attitude toward the treatment of the site, with Herrmann noting that "Brazilian archaeology denies altogether the existence of Phoenician inscription in any part of the country whatsoever."<ref name=her214 />

